excerpt: Castle & museum detailing the history of the port, including various scale models of the city.
detail_description: The Château des ducs de Bretagne, a grand castle located in the heart of Nantes, has a rich history dating back to 1207. It was once the seat of the province of Brittany and home to the Dukes of Brittany for over three centuries. Designated as a national historical monument, it now houses the Nantes History Museum, showcasing more than 850 artifacts that depict the region's diverse heritage.
name: Château des ducs de Bretagne

excerpt: 1840s shopping mall featuring Renaissance-inspired architecture & 2 levels of upscale boutiques.
detail_description: Passage Pommeraye, constructed in 1843, is a stunning shopping arcade that stands out for its Renaissance-inspired architecture and upscale boutiques. This historical masterpiece features an elaborate staircase, statues, and ornaments across three floors, creating a maze of gilded galleries. Visitors can explore fashion showrooms, cake shops, and jewelry or leather workshops within this enchanting setting.
name: Passage Pommeraye

excerpt: Artistic park attraction with a giant elephant & heron, inspired by Jules Verne & Leonardo da Vinci.
detail_description: Les Machines de l'Île is an imaginative and interactive park attraction in Nantes, inspired by the works of Jules Verne and Leonardo da Vinci. The park features a giant mechanical elephant that walks, trumpets, sprays water, and even spits fire. Visitors can also explore a laboratory of nature-inspired machines and enjoy a three-story carousel of marine machines.
name: Les Machines de l'Île
address: Parc des Chantiers, Bd Léon Bureau, 44200 Nantes, France

excerpt: Nantes, a city on the Loire River in the Upper Brittany region of western France, has a long history as a port and industrial center. It's home to the restored, medieval Château des Ducs de Bretagne, where the Dukes of Brittany once lived. The castle is now a local history museum with multimedia exhibits, as well as a walkway atop its fortified ramparts.
detail_description: Nantes, located in western France along the Loire River, is a city with a rich history as a port and industrial hub. Visitors can explore the restored medieval Château des Ducs de Bretagne, now a local history museum with multimedia exhibits and walkways atop its fortified ramparts.
name: Nantes

excerpt: Museum of fine art with collections ranging from the 13th century to the modern video installation.
detail_description: The Musée d’arts de Nantes is a must-visit for art enthusiasts, boasting an extensive collection that spans from the 13th century to modern video installations. Established by Napoleon in 1801 and recently reopened after a six-year renovation, this museum showcases an impressive array of masterpieces from renowned artists such as Tintoretto, Rubens, Monet, Rodin, Kandinsky, and Chagall.
name: Musée d’arts de Nantes

excerpt: Museum dedicated to the novelist Jules Verne, housing memorabilia, manuscripts & a reading room.
detail_description: The Jules Verne Museum is a tribute to the renowned novelist, showcasing his personal belongings, manuscripts, and a reading room. Housed in a grand 19th-century mansion overlooking the Loire River, this museum offers an immersive experience for fans of Verne's wildly imaginative Voyages Extraordinaires books. Visitors can explore an eclectic collection of books, games, portraits, and documents belonging to the writer.
name: Jules Verne Museum

excerpt: Catholic cathedral built between 1434 & the late 19th century, with sculpted tombs & stained glass.
detail_description: The Cathédrale Saint-Pierre-et-Saint-Paul de Nantes, a stunning example of Gothic and Renaissance architecture, dominates the skyline of Nantes with its grandeur. Construction began in 1434 and spanned nearly five centuries, culminating in 1893. This architectural marvel boasts intricate stone carvings and breathtaking stained glass windows that create an atmosphere of awe. The cathedral has played a significant role in history, witnessing events like the wedding of Anne of Brittany.
name: Cathédrale Saint-Pierre-et-Saint-Paul de Nantes

excerpt: Cultural center with a bookshop & a bar in a converted biscuit factory, hosting art & performances.
detail_description: Le Lieu Unique is a vibrant cultural center located in Nantes, housed in a former biscuit factory. It stands out as a unique venue that offers an eclectic mix of artistic experiences, including theater, dance, literature, architecture, and circus performances. The space also features a bar, restaurant, bookshop, and even a hammam for visitors to unwind.
name: Le Lieu Unique

excerpt: Trentemoult is a former fishing village on the Loire River, known for colorful 3-story houses with red-tiled roofs, and gardens filled with palm trees. Lining the busy Quai Marcel Boissard are traditional bistros, crêperies, and cafes, and seagulls circling above fishing boats. On the river, Roman Signer’s red 7-meter-high Pendulum is an art installation that steadily ticks each second with its huge swinging hand.
detail_description: Trentemoult, a charming former fishing village situated along the Loire River, is renowned for its picturesque 3-story houses adorned with red-tiled roofs and palm-filled gardens. The bustling Quai Marcel Boissard is lined with traditional bistros, crêperies, and cafes where visitors can watch seagulls soaring above fishing boats. Additionally, the river features Roman Signer’s striking art installation Pendulum, a towering red structure that swings each second.
name: Trentemoult

excerpt: This monument is dedicated to abolitionists & the victims of the Atlantic slave trade.
detail_description: The Memorial to the Abolition of Slavery in Nantes pays tribute to abolitionists and the victims of the Atlantic slave trade. The city, once France's largest slave port, saw numerous ships depart for Africa daily. Although slavery was abolished in 1848, it wasn't until the 1990s that Nantes confronted its dark history.
name: Memorial to the Abolition of Slavery
address: Passerelle Victor-Schoelcher, Quai de la Fosse, 44000 Nantes, France

detail_description: Pl. du Bouffay is a bustling square located in the heart of Nantes' oldest district, offering a glimpse into local life and culture. The area is renowned for its well-preserved medieval architecture and narrow winding streets, creating an atmospheric setting for exploration. Visitors can immerse themselves in the district's rich history while strolling along pedestrian streets lined with 15th-century half-timbered houses, vibrant restaurants, and lively nightlife venues.
name: Pl. du Bouffay

excerpt: Vibrant, historic Bouffay is home to medieval buildings and Haussmann-style apartments, as well as eclectic boutiques and the Galeries Lafayette department store. The area buzzes at night with French restaurants, bars, and brasseries. The centuries-old Château des Ducs de Bretagne houses the Nantes History Museum, with multimedia exhibits, and Nantes Cathedral features a Renaissance tomb and an 11th-century crypt.
detail_description: Bouffay is a vibrant and historic neighborhood in Nantes, known for its medieval buildings, Haussmann-style apartments, and eclectic boutiques. At night, the area comes alive with French restaurants, bars, and brasseries. The Château des Ducs de Bretagne houses the Nantes History Museum with multimedia exhibits. Nearby is the Nantes Cathedral featuring a Renaissance tomb and an 11th-century crypt.
name: Bouffay

detail_description: Le Lieu Unique is a versatile cultural space in Nantes, offering a diverse range of artistic experiences. From art exhibitions and concerts to dance performances, it celebrates art in all its forms. Additionally, visitors can explore the Jules Verne museum at the top of Butte Sainte-Anne and enjoy breathtaking views from Le Nid atop the Tour de Bretagne.
name: Le Lieu Unique
address: Rue de la Biscuiterie, 44000 Nantes, France

excerpt: Palm-house tours, plus trails amid camellias & magnolias in a 19th-century park & botanical gardens.
detail_description: Nestled in the heart of Nantes, the Jardin des Plantes is a stunning botanical garden that offers a serene escape from the hustle and bustle of city life. Established in the 18th century, this lush oasis boasts an impressive collection of around 11,000 plant species, including vibrant camellias and majestic magnolias. Visitors can wander through its picturesque trails or relax amidst its tranquil environment, soaking up the beauty of nature.
name: Botanical Garden

excerpt: Decommissioned navy destroyer & museum offering engine room, weapons systems & crew-area tours.
detail_description: The French destroyer Maillé-Brézé stands as a remarkable testament to maritime history, inviting visitors to step aboard this decommissioned warship turned museum. Located in Nantes, it offers an immersive experience into the life of sailors and the naval operations that once took place on its decks.
name: French destroyer Maillé-Brézé
address: Quai de la Fosse, 44000 Nantes, France

excerpt: Museum exhibiting Thomas Dobrée's collection of art, books & coins in a 19th-century palace.
detail_description: Located in the upscale Graslin neighborhood of Nantes, France, Musée Dobrée is a historical museum set to reopen in May 2024 after being closed for 13 years. Housed in a 15th-century manor house and neo-medieval palace, it showcases over 2,000 artworks spanning from prehistoric times to the 20th century across more than half an acre of exhibition space.
name: Musée Dobrée

excerpt: Brasserie fare offered in a storied, elegant brasserie that has an art nouveau interior.
detail_description: La Cigale is a century-old brasserie in Nantes, known for its elegant Art Nouveau decor. The restaurant's interior features warm carpeting, impressive carved woodwork, and period ceramics. It has been frequented by surrealists like Andre Breton and Jacques Prevert, as well as filmmaker Jacques Demy who shot his film "Lola" there in 1961.
name: La Cigale

excerpt: 1970s skyscraper & the tallest building in Nantes, with a quirky, bird-themed bar & rooftop terrace.
detail_description: Tour Bretagne is a tall skyscraper located in the heart of downtown Nantes. It comprises of eight elevators and seven escalators which makes it an easy and fast way to get to the top. There is also a rooftop terrace with beautiful views of the city that is free to use.
name: Tour Bretagne

excerpt: Park with rhododendrons, camellias & magnolias, plus an art gallery & cafe in an 18th-century manor.
detail_description: Parc de Procé is a delightful green sanctuary nestled in Nantes, perfect for those seeking a peaceful retreat from the city's hustle. Spanning 12 hectares, this beautifully landscaped park features an array of vibrant rhododendrons, camellias, and magnolias that bloom throughout the seasons. Designed by renowned landscape architect Dominique Noisette in 1866, it showcases classic English garden aesthetics with its sprawling lawns and majestic trees offering shade for leisurely strolls.
name: Parc de Procé

excerpt: Grand, 1800s church on the site of a 1200s chapel, with a soaring nave & stained-glass windows.
detail_description: Nestled in the heart of Nantes, the Basilique Saint-Nicolas de Nantes is a stunning neo-Gothic church that stands as a testament to both history and architectural beauty. Constructed between 1844 and 1869 on the site of a 13th-century chapel, this grand edifice features an impressive nave adorned with exquisite stained-glass windows. Although it suffered significant damage during World War II, dedicated restoration efforts have preserved its elegance for visitors to admire today.
name: Basilique Saint-Nicolas de Nantes

detail_description: The Le Hangar à Bananes is an association or organization that preserves history by hosting trendy restaurants, bars and clubs. The building was formerly a banana-ripening warehouse, and today it is an excellent place to visit while in Nantes.
name: Le Hangar à Bananes
address: Hangar à Bananes, 21 Quai des Antilles, 44200 Nantes, France

excerpt: 1.7 hectare island & park, created in 1831 & featuring a Japanese-style Zen garden with exhibitions.
detail_description: Nestled in the heart of Nantes, the Île de Versailles is a 1.7-hectare island and park that dates back to 1831. One of its main attractions is a serene Japanese-style Zen garden, offering a tranquil escape from the bustling city streets. The island also features a traditional tea house called Maison de l'Erdre, which hosts exhibitions showcasing the local flora and fauna along the river.
name: île de Versailles

excerpt: Elegant neoclassical building with Napoleonic-era collections of animal bones, taxidermy & minerals.
detail_description: The Nantes Natural History Museum is housed in an elegant neoclassical building and features collections of animal bones, taxidermy, minerals, and multimedia displays that showcase the city's history. The museum reopened in 2016 after extensive renovations and offers visitors the chance to explore 19th-century interiors while learning about Nantes' history through various exhibitions.
name: Natural History Museum

excerpt: Paths & boat rides around a Zen garden with cherry trees on a landscaped island in the Erdre River.
detail_description: Île de Versailles is a serene Japanese-inspired garden located on an artificial island in the Erdre River, offering visitors a tranquil and harmonious escape from urban life. The carefully manicured gardens, traditional Japanese architecture, and serene water features create an enchanting oasis for contemplation. Wandering through winding paths and crossing wooden bridges immerses visitors in lush greenery and the soothing sound of flowing water.
name: Île de Versailles

excerpt: Ornate, historic church with a bell tower, a 17th-century altar & Gothic stained-glass windows.
detail_description: Eglise Sainte-Croix is a historic church located in the Quartier Bouffay of Nantes. It is owned by the Diocese of Nantes and features a 17th-century Baroque facade, a bell tower, and vibrant stained-glass windows. The church has a little garden that was once part of its old cloisters and cemetery, offering a peaceful retreat for visitors. Inside, the church boasts an impressive Gothic-style nave and houses the only surviving seventh-century altar.
name: Église Sainte-Croix de Nantes

excerpt: Linear park with a statue of war hero General Cambronne, lined by trees & neoclassical buildings.
detail_description: Cours Cambronne is a stunning linear park located in the heart of Nantes, surrounded by neoclassical buildings and lined with beautiful trees. At its center stands a statue of General Pierre Cambronne, a war hero injured in the Battle of Waterloo. The square is part of a new city district built in the 18th century and features 16 magnificent mansions listed as French historic monuments.
name: Cours Cambronne

detail_description: The Théâtre Graslin, located in Nantes, was constructed in the late 18th century by architect Mathurin Crucy and can accommodate 822 people. Despite being ravaged by fire shortly after its inauguration in 1788, it was rebuilt in 1811 and underwent a second restoration in 2003. The theater's design is predominantly Italian, featuring a facade with Roman and Greek architectural elements and eight imperial columns.
name: Théâtre Graslin

excerpt: Landmark 1930s market hall selling fruit, veg & seafood, with cheese & charcuterie specialists.
detail_description: Talensac Market is a historic 1930s market hall in Nantes, France. With over 100 vendors offering a wide range of products including cheeses, meats, pastries, chocolates, and ready-made dishes, it provides an authentic glimpse into local life. As the oldest and largest market in Nantes, it is renowned for its abundance of fresh seafood, vegetables, cheese, wine, and other delicacies.
name: Talensac Market

detail_description: Place Royale is a charming and historic square in Quebec City, Canada. It is known for its beautiful 17th-century architecture, cobblestone streets, and lively atmosphere. The area is surrounded by quaint shops, cafes, and restaurants, making it a popular spot for both locals and tourists to explore. Visitors can immerse themselves in the rich history of the square while enjoying the picturesque surroundings.
name: Place Royale

detail_description: Nestled in the heart of Nantes, the Jardin des Plantes is an idyllic escape that invites you to unwind amidst its stunning natural scenery. This enchanting botanical garden offers free entry, making it accessible for everyone. With a charming community atmosphere, it's a beloved gathering spot for locals and families alike. As you wander through its lush pathways, you'll find children playing and visitors leisurely exploring, all contributing to the garden's warm and inviting ambiance.
name: Jardin des Plantes

excerpt: City park with a Japanese-style pagoda, greenhouses for tropical plants & play areas for children.
detail_description: Parc du Grand Blottereau in Nantes is a sprawling 22-hectare park, making it the largest in the city. It features a Japanese-style pagoda, tropical plant greenhouses, and play areas for children. The park has an exotic ambiance and serves as a learning ground for plant enthusiasts due to its association with the horticultural high school of Nantes.
name: Parc du Grand Blottereau

excerpt: Planetarium with a state-of-the-art projector system, astronomical simulator & child-friendly shows.
detail_description: The Planetarium De Nantes offers a cutting-edge projector system and engaging shows suitable for both adults and children. Visitors can delve into the mysteries of the solar system, black holes, and the life cycle of stars. Special events are organized to commemorate significant astronomical phenomena such as eclipses and meteor showers. The planetarium also hosts 'astronomy for little ones,' which was highly praised by visitors with young children.
name: Planetarium De Nantes

detail_description: Nantes, a vibrant and youthful city located between Brittany and the Loire Valley, is known for its creative and playful atmosphere. Just 30 minutes from the ocean and easily accessible from Paris and other European capitals, Nantes offers a mix of cultural and touristic activities.
name: Nantes

excerpt: Grand pedestrian square set around an ornamental fountain representing local & regional mythology.
detail_description: Place Royale is a grand 18th-century square located in Nantes, featuring an ornamental fountain that represents local and regional mythology. The square's symmetrical layout and stone facades give it a timeless feel, and on sunny days, it becomes a lively gathering place for locals and visitors who relax at nearby cafe terraces or gather around the fountain. In addition to its architectural elegance, Place Royale offers a vibrant atmosphere with bars, restaurants, bookstores, movie theaters, and boutiques.
name: Place Royale

detail_description: HAB Galerie, situated at the western tip of Ile de Nantes, is housed in the industrial shed unit known as Hangar a Bananes, which historically stored bananas and pineapples from Africa. The gallery is a bright and spacious venue that showcases contemporary art through three to four annual exhibitions. Visitors can also explore a well-stocked shop offering art books, novels, and various other items.
name: HAB Galerie

excerpt: Expansive museum tracing the city's history, including exhibits on the French slave trade.
detail_description: Nestled in the picturesque city of Nantes, the Musée d'histoire de Nantes is a treasure trove for anyone passionate about history and culture. This expansive museum invites visitors to embark on an enlightening journey through the city's multifaceted past, including significant exhibits that delve into topics like the French slave trade and maritime history. Housed within the stunning Château des Ducs de Bretagne, it features a rich collection of artifacts ranging from medieval times to modernity.
name: Musée d'histoire de Nantes

excerpt: Long-standing creperie with outdoor tables, serving up sweet crepes, savory galettes & Breton cider.
detail_description: Crêperie Heb Ken is a long-standing establishment in Nantes, the capital of western France and the former capital of Brittany. This charming creperie offers a variety of sweet crepes, savory galettes, and Breton cider made with local ingredients such as ham, goat cheese, strawberry jam, chocolate, and traditional salted butter. The menu features affordable options starting at 2.70 euros.
name: Crêperie Heb Ken

detail_description: Located in the Pays de la Loire region of Nantes, Île de Nantes is a captivating destination featuring the remarkable Machines de l'Ile. This ongoing artistic venture brings to life colossal mechanical creatures inspired by the visions of Jules Verne and Leonardo da Vinci. Visitors can marvel at these creations, with some even offering the opportunity to test or ride them, such as the towering Great Elephant and the Marine Carousel adorned with sea creatures.
name: Île de Nantes

excerpt: Tropical palms, banana trees & an artificial cascade in a disused quarry surrounded by steep cliffs.
detail_description: Jardin Extraordinaire is a newly created botanical garden located in the rebellious district of Chantenay in Nantes. It is set in an old quarry surrounded by steep cliffs and features tropical palms, banana trees, and an artificial cascade. The garden offers small pathways for wandering and a children's play area. Visitors can also climb a long staircase to reach the top of the quarry for stunning views.
name: Le Jardin Extraordinaire

excerpt: Relaxed brasserie with outdoor tables, dishing up classic French eats for breakfast, lunch & dinner.
detail_description: Café des Plantes is a relaxed brasserie conveniently serving classic French dishes all day. Located near the train station, it offers a casual dining experience with friendly staff and fast service. The diner-style cuisine with a French twist is very tasty, and the generous portions at fair prices make it a popular choice for locals and travelers alike.
name: Café des Plantes

excerpt: Enduring outpost serving crepes & galettes in a warm, rustic locale dating back to the 15th century.
detail_description: Au Vieux Quimper is a historic eatery that has been serving traditional crepes and galettes for over 30 years. Located in the charming Bouffay district, this rustic establishment dates back to the 15th century, adding to its allure. Despite its enduring popularity, the restaurant's warm ambiance and delicious offerings continue to attract both locals and visitors alike.
name: Au Vieux Quimper
address: 10 Rue de la Baclerie, 44000 Nantes, France

detail_description: Cheese & Friends in Nantes is a must-visit spot for tourists looking to unwind with some delicious cheese and wine. Visitors have raved about the attentive and helpful staff who recommended delectable options not listed on the menu, such as the perfect mozzarella for a warm evening. The local IPA and rose cider were also highly praised.
name: Cheese & Friends

excerpt: Vast, contemporary concert venue hosting big-name international music acts, plus sport events.
detail_description: The Zenith Nantes Metropole is a modern and spacious performing arts venue that frequently hosts world-renowned musicians as well as sporting events. Its size allows for quick and easy access to amenities such as bars, making it an enjoyable experience for attendees. While some guests have noted that the dressing rooms may lack adequate heating facilities, overall the theater provides a fantastic space for an exceptional concert experience.
name: Zenith Nantes Metropole

excerpt: Museum dedicated to the printing process, with historical presses & lithographs on display.
detail_description: This museum is dedicated to the printing process and has historical presses and lithographs on display. The tour takes a long time, but it provides a great insight into the entire process of printing. The guide is very knowledgeable and passionate about his craft, and by demonstrating every machine in the museum you get a really good understanding of how everything works. The museum is definitely recommended for anyone interested in printing history!
name: Musée Atelier de l'Imprimerie de Nantes
address: 24 Quai de la Fosse, 44000 Nantes, France

excerpt: Sprawling, tree-filled park featuring a château & a cemetery, plus an alpine garden & a large pond.
detail_description: Parc de la Gaudinière in Nantes, France is a sprawling and serene park that offers a variety of attractions for visitors. The park features a château, an alpine garden, and a large pond, making it an ideal destination for nature lovers. It also boasts playgrounds, picnic areas, and beautiful gardens. The park is perfect for outdoor activities such as hiking along the Cens river or enjoying sports and picnics on its well-maintained grounds.
name: Parc de la Gaudinière

detail_description: Notre-Dame de Bon-Port is a Gothic-style place of worship located near Nantes Cathedral, by the river. During World War II, it also functioned as a prison. The church houses various religious relics, including Saint Anne's head and pieces of Jesus' cross. It boasts stunning stained glass windows, remarkable sculptures, and inlaid parquet flooring in its main aisles.
name: Notre-Dame de Bon-Port

detail_description: Porte Saint-Pierre in Nantes is a historical site that showcases archaeological remnants dating back to the 3rd to 15th century. It serves as a gateway to Cathedrale Saint-Pierre-et-Saint-Paul, which began construction in 1434 and suffered fire damage in 2020. Despite being temporarily closed, the cathedral still exudes majesty.
name: Porte Saint-Pierre

detail_description: Located at Hangar à Bananes, Theatre 100 names is an iconic performance venue on the Ile de Nantes, opened in 2013. Unlike other modern theaters, it is designed in the spirit of a 17th-century Italian theater. With its 340-seat capacity, adorned with golden ornaments and balconies, this venue hosts a variety of performances including comedies, one-man shows, humorous concerts, and children's shows.
name: Theatre 100 names
